### 版本 1: Standard Polish (优化语言与逻辑流畅度)

在这个版本中，我们将口语化的表达（如 "Does learning to speak... imply..."）转化为更严谨的陈述，并精简了定义的描述。

```latex
\section{Empirical Analysis of Perception Gap}
\label{sec:motivation}

To quantify the misalignment between textual generation and visual attention, we conduct a pilot study investigating two key questions:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{(RQ1)} Is correct visual reasoning causally dependent on focused visual attention?
    \item \textbf{(RQ2)} Do teacher and student models exhibit a ``perception gap'' in visual trajectories despite similar textual outputs?
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Visual Attention as a Prerequisite for Reasoning}
\label{subsec:visual_bounds}

\textbf{Definition 3.1 (Visual Focusing Score).} Let $I$ be the input image and $B_{gt}$ the ground-truth bounding box. We define the Visual Focusing Score $S_{focus}$ as the proportion of the aggregated attention mass $\mathcal{A}_{traj} \in \mathbb{R}^{H \times W}$ falling within the target region:
\begin{equation}
    S_{focus} = \frac{\sum_{(u,v) \in B_{gt}} \mathcal{A}_{traj}(u,v)}{\sum_{(u,v) \in I} \mathcal{A}_{traj}(u,v)}
\end{equation}
A higher $S_{focus}$ implies the model relies on verified visual evidence rather than language priors.

\noindent \textbf{Observation: Visual Attention Dictates Performance.}
Analyzing Qwen2.5-VL-32B~\cite{Qwen2.5} on 1,000 samples from Visual-CoT~\citep{shao2024visual} (Figure~\ref{fig:accuracy_curve}) reveals a strict dependency:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Positive Correlation:} Reasoning accuracy improves monotonically with $S_{focus}$. Correct samples exhibit significantly higher attention concentration (\textbf{15.89\%}) compared to incorrect ones (\textbf{11.84\%}), a relative gap of $\sim$34\%.
    \item \textbf{Failure of Blind Guessing:} Samples with negligible visual attention ($S_{focus} < 1\%$) result in hallucinations, confirming that models cannot bypass visual grounding for complex tasks.
\end{itemize}

\begin{figure}[t]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.95\linewidth]{figures/accuracy_vs_energy_curve_fine.png}
  \caption{\textbf{Impact of Visual Attention.} The monotonic increase in accuracy with higher $S_{focus}$ confirms that effective visual grounding is a prerequisite for correct reasoning.}
  \label{fig:accuracy_curve}
  \vspace{-5mm}
\end{figure}

\noindent \fbox{
    \parbox{0.95\linewidth}{
        \textbf{Observation 1:} \textit{\textbf{Visual attention is determinative.}} Focused visual grounding ($S_{focus}$) is a necessary condition for success. Models fail to reason correctly without actively ``looking'' at the relevant evidence.
    }
}

\subsection{The Perception Gap Between Teachers and Students}
\label{subsec:perception_gap}

We investigate whether standard Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT) transfers the teacher's visual reasoning process using the same experimental setup.

\paragraph{Analysis of Attention Divergence.}
We categorize generated tokens into \textbf{Functional}, \textbf{Object}, and \textbf{Attribute} groups based on visual semantic reliance. We compare the Teacher ($M_T$) and Student ($M_S$) via the KL divergence of their attention maps and the Cosine Distance of their hidden states. As shown in Figure~\ref{fig:attention_gap}, we observe a distinct decoupling:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Attention Drift on Visual Concepts:} Attention divergence increases with visual complexity. While Functional tokens align well ($\mu=1.11$), Attribute tokens show maximal misalignment ($\mu \approx 1.39$), indicating the student struggles to locate fine-grained details.
    \item \textbf{The ``Blind Guessing'' Phenomenon:} Despite surging attention divergence, the hidden state similarity remains stable (Cosine Distance $\approx 0.52\text{-}0.55$). This implies the student mimics the teacher's textual representations (\textit{what to say}) without inheriting the visual attention (\textit{where to look}).
\end{itemize}

\noindent \fbox{
    \parbox{0.95\linewidth}{
        \textbf{Observation 2:} \textit{\textbf{Textual mimicry does not guarantee visual understanding.}} SFT transfers textual patterns but fails to bridge the ``Perception Gap,'' leading to students that rely on language priors rather than active observation.
    }
}

\begin{figure}[t]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.9\linewidth]{figures/attention_divergence.png}
  \vspace{-0.5em}
  \caption{\textbf{The Perception-Reasoning Gap.} While textual representations remain aligned (stable Cosine Distance), visual attention diverges significantly on attribute-heavy tokens, revealing that \textit{mimicry $\neq$ grounding}.}
  \label{fig:attention_gap}
  \vspace{-5mm}
\end{figure}
```

